# 🧠 1. PROMPTS TO PREVENT ARCHITECTURAL DRIFT

These are **guardrail prompts** you can reuse anytime you feel the system getting “too layered” or inconsistent.

You can literally paste these at the start of a session.

---

## 🔒 PROMPT 1 — “NO NEW SYSTEMS WITHOUT JUSTIFICATION”

> Before proposing any new file, layer, or subsystem, first classify it as one of:
>
> * State
> * Navigation
> * Effects
> * Actions
> * Experience Layer (scene/audio/choreo)
>
> If it does not clearly belong to one of these, it is either:
>
> * redundant
> * a merge candidate
> * or unnecessary abstraction
>
> Do not introduce new architectural categories without explicitly showing why existing ones are insufficient.

---

## 🔒 PROMPT 2 — “MERGE-FIRST RULE”

> If a new feature overlaps with an existing system (routing, lifecycle, scene management, effects, or choreography), prioritize merging or extending existing systems instead of creating a new subsystem.

---

## 🔒 PROMPT 3 — “NO PARALLEL ORCHESTRATION SYSTEMS”

> There must only be one orchestration spine in the engine.
>
> If a proposed system:
>
> * schedules transitions
> * controls scene flow
> * or sequences gameplay steps
>
> it must integrate into the existing pipeline, not exist alongside it.

---

## 🔒 PROMPT 4 — “DEPENDENCY DISCIPLINE CHECK”

> Before approving a new module, verify:
>
> * Does it depend on router?
> * Does it depend on lifecycle?
> * Does it duplicate effects or actions?
>
> If yes to more than one orchestration layer, it is likely a duplication risk.

---

## 🔒 PROMPT 5 — “ENGINE VS FEATURE TEST”

> Ask:
> “Is this an engine primitive, or a gameplay feature?”
>
> If it is gameplay, it must NOT become a new system layer.

---

## 🔒 PROMPT 6 — “ONE SOURCE OF TRUTH RULE”

> For any domain (inventory, scene state, audio, flags):
> there must be exactly one authoritative system.
>
> Everything else is a consumer or adapter.

